        </nav>

        <article class="prose max-w-none">
          <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">Hong Kong Car Tax Guide: First Registration Tax and Motor Vehicle Tax</h1>
          <p class="text-lg text-body dark:text-muted">Last updated: July 2026 | 10 min read</p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Hong Kong's car tax regime is designed to manage traffic congestion and environmental impact, resulting in some of the highest vehicle ownership costs in the world. The primary taxes are First Registration Tax and Motor Vehicle Tax, along with related registration fees and road charges. This guide covers first registration tax rates, motor vehicle tax, how taxes are calculated, exemptions, electric vehicle benefits, and how to use a Hong Kong car tax calculator for estimates.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">First Registration Tax (FRT)</h2>
            <p>First Registration Tax is levied on motor vehicles when they are first registered in Hong Kong. The FRT applies to passenger cars, commercial vehicles, motorcycles, and motor tricycles. The tax is calculated based on the vehicle's market value, with rates that increase in tiered bands. The objective of FRT is to discourage vehicle purchases and reduce traffic congestion. For most passenger cars, FRT can represent a substantial portion of the overall cost of ownership. The Commissioner of Transport is responsible for administering FRT and publishes detailed tables for calculation.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Motor Vehicle Tax (MVT)</h2>
            <p>Motor Vehicle Tax is an annual tax payable by the registered owner of a motor vehicle. The MVT is calculated based on the engine capacity of the vehicle. Smaller engine vehicles are taxed at lower rates, incentivizing fuel efficiency and lower emissions. The MVT is payable each year when the vehicle license is renewed. Late payment results in penalties and surcharges. Combined with other operating costs such as fuel, parking, and insurance, the vehicle ownership cost in Hong Kong is substantial.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How to Calculate Car Tax in Hong Kong</h2>
            <p>To calculate the total tax on a new car in Hong Kong, you need to consider FRT, MVT, registration fees, and potentially other duties. The FRT is determined by the vehicle's carbon content classification, with higher rates for vehicles with greater carbon footprints. The MVT is determined by engine capacity. The total cost also includes the vehicle purchase price, insurance, and financing costs. Using a Hong Kong car tax calculator simplifies this process by allowing you to input the vehicle value and engine capacity to get an accurate tax estimate. Always verify the latest rates with the Transport Department or <a href="https://www.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">gov.hk</a>.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-keyword">Exemptions</h2>
            <p>Certain vehicles are exempt from First Registration Tax and Motor Vehicle Tax. For example, vehicles with specific commercial classifications, emergency vehicles, and certain government-owned vehicles are exempt. Additionally, vehicles imported by visiting forces or for private use by certain diplomats may qualify for relief. The Transport Department maintains a list of exempt categories on its website. If you believe your vehicle qualifies for an exemption, you must apply for confirmation before registration.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Electric Vehicle Benefits</h2>
            <p>Hong Kong actively promotes electric vehicles (EVs) through various incentives. For EVs, the First Registration Tax concession is the most significant benefit. Until April 1, 2027, all newly registered purely electric private passenger cars enjoy a full waiver of the First Registration Tax, subject to a maximum value cap for each vehicle. This concession makes EVs much more affordable compared to conventional vehicles. In addition, EVs pay reduced Motor Vehicle Tax rates or are exempt in some cases. The government has repeatedly extended EV concessions as part of its Hong Kong Roadmap on Popularisation of Electric Vehicles. Check <a href="https://www.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">gov.hk</a> for the latest cap and expiry date before purchasing.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">When to Pay and Penalties</h2>
            <p>First Registration Tax is paid at the time of vehicle registration. Motor Vehicle Tax is payable annually when renewing your vehicle license. Late payment of MVT incurs a penalty of 20% of the tax due, and failure to pay may result in the vehicle being deregistered. To avoid penalties, pay your MVT before the expiry date shown on your vehicle license. You can renew your license and pay MVT through designated payment channels or at a vehicle licensing office.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How is First Registration Tax calculated?</h3>
            <p>FRT is calculated based on the vehicle's carbon content classification and market value. Higher carbon intensity and higher value result in higher tax. Use our car tax calculator for an estimate based on your vehicle's details.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Is there a First Registration Tax exemption for electric vehicles?</h3>
            <p>Yes, all newly registered purely electric private passenger cars enjoy full FRT concession, subject to a maximum value cap. Check the latest announcement on <a href="https://www.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">gov.hk</a> for the updated cap.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What is the motor vehicle tax rate in Hong Kong?</h3>
            <p>MVT is based on engine capacity. Smaller vehicles pay less than larger vehicles. The exact rates are published by the Transport Department and vary from year to year.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Do I pay both First Registration Tax and Motor Vehicle Tax?</h3>
            <p>Yes, when you first register a vehicle you pay FRT as a one-time tax. Each year when renewing the vehicle license, you pay MVT.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Can I defer motor vehicle tax payments?</h3>
            <p>No. MVT must be paid before the vehicle license expires. Failure to pay results in penalties and possible deregistration of the vehicle.</p>
